                <p>After eight years, <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/games/hollow-knight-silksong/" data-ref-id="5000-493311">Silksong</a> is here, and it's tough. Very tough, actually, to the point where some players believe it's much harder than its 2017 predecessor, <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/games/hollow-knight/" data-ref-id="5000-448603">Hollow Knight</a>. That difficulty increase is exactly by design, though, according to Team Cherry in a new interview.</p><p>As <a href="https://www.dexerto.com/gaming/hollow-knight-silksong-devs-address-difficulty-concerns-3252994/" data-target="true" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">spotted by Dexerto</a> while attending Melbourne's ACMI Game Worlds exhibition, Team Cherry co-director Ari Gibson and developer William Pellen spoke to the exhibition's co-curator Jini Maxwell for a new book. In the book, <a href="https://shop.acmi.net.au/products/acmi-guide-hollow-knight-silk-song-softcover?srsltid=AfmBOorolCkbcsFRBiulJZC98MkEWBMccyccEhiNRv3TVDPuowpnL0kX" data-target="true" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">the ACMI Guide: Hollow Knight Silksong</a>, Gibson and Pellen contextualize why the sequel is harder than the original, and it's actually because of Hornet.</p>



    
